#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "Grammar and Punctuation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:40
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Distinctives for technical writing** as outlined in the Chicago Manual of Style include the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:47
msgid "Double quotation marks (“Chicago style”) rather than single quotation marks (‘Oxford style’)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:47
msgid "Periods and commas go inside quotation marks “like this,” rather than “like this”."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:47
msgid "The em dash {shift}+{option}+{-} has no spaces before or after—like this—and is preferred for parenthetical phrases."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:47
msgid "Use a serial comma before the “and” in a list of three items: “Peas, mustard, and carrots.”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:47
msgid "Headings should be generally made in headline-style capitalization: Capitalize the first and last words, as well as all nouns, pronouns, verbs, and adverbs. If your document works better with sentence-style capitalization, perhaps because you make frequent references to acronyms, just make it consistent within the entire document."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:47
msgid "Headings do not need a period or semicolon at the end, even with sentence-style capitalization, unless ending in an abbreviation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "Voice and Tone"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "**Plain language.** This can be described as a *less-conversational* style. Most of our documentation fits within this standard."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "Avoid metaphors and idioms."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "Say what you mean in as few words as possible."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "Identify and avoid unnecessarily technical terms. Consider that your audience is mostly people who have some familiarity with the subject matter, but may not be subject-matter experts."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "Exceptions to plain language:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '        * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "For documentation addressed to newcomers or beginners, or for writing content such as a blog post, a more conversational style is appropriate."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '        * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "For documentation addressed to advanced users or API (Application Programming Interface) documentation, a more formal or terse wording style is appropriate."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "**Inclusive language.**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "Language use evolves over time. Certain words have evolved to carry negative connotations so documentation should be rewritten to use new words."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '        * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "*Master/slave* becomes *primary/secondary* or an agreed upon organizational standard."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '        * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "*Blacklist/whitelist* becomes *blocklist/allowlist* or an agreed upon organizational standard."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '        * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "You may think of other relevant examples as you create documentation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "When speaking of a person of *unknown* or *non-binary* gender, it is now considered acceptable to use “they” as a singular pronoun."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "When speaking of one’s capabilities, frame answers as *abilities* rather than *limitations.* For example, if you are wondering whether we have documentation about running Steam on Rocky Linux, the answer is not just “no.” Rather, “Sounds like that’s a great place for you to create something to add to our tree!”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:65
msgid "**Avoid contractions.** This assists with translation efforts. The exception to this is when writing something in a more conversational tone, such as blog posts or welcome instructions for new members of the community."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "Formatting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:68
#, no-wrap
msgid "Dates"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:71
msgid "When possible use the name of the month in the format {day} {Month} {year}. However, {Month} {day}, {year} is also acceptable to resolve clarity or appearance issues. Either way, to avoid creating confusion, write out month names rather than using a series of numbers.  For example: 24 January 2023, but January 24, 2023 is also acceptable—with both preferable over 1/24/2023 or 24/01/2023."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "Single-step Procedures"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:75
msgid "If you have a procedure with only one step, use a bullet rather than a number. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:77
msgid "Implement this idea and move on."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "Graphical Interface Language"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:81
msgid "Text instructions regarding a UI: When describing a command to be entered into a user interface, use the word “enter” rather than “put” or “type.” Use a codeblock to write out the command (i.e., set it off with backticks):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:84
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Example Markdown text*\n"
"`In the **commit message** box, enter update_thisdoc.`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:86
msgid "Names of UI elements: **Bold** names of UI elements such as buttons, menu items, names of dialog boxes, and more, even if the word will not be clickable:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Example Markdown text*\n"
"`In the **Format** menu, click **Line Spacing**.`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:90
#, no-wrap
msgid "Structure"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "Starting content of each guide, or page/chapter of a book"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:99
msgid "**Abstract.** A brief statement of what to expect from this page"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:99
msgid "**Objectives.** A bulleted list of what this page will convey to the reader"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:99
msgid "**Skills** required/learned."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:99
msgid "**Difficulty level.** 1 star for easy, 2 for intermediate, etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:99
msgid "**Reading time.** Divide the number of words in your document by a reading rate of 75 words per minute to determine this number."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:103
msgid "Within Markdown, admonitions are a way to put information into a box to highlight it. They are not essential to documentation, but they are a tool you may find useful. Learn more about admonitions from our [Rocky Formatting doc](../rockydocs_formatting/)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:104
#, no-wrap
msgid "Accessibility"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "*The following standards enhance accessibility for those using accommodations, such as screen readers, to access our documentation.*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:108
#: ../src/docs/release_notes/8_8.md:15 ../src/docs/release_notes/9_2.md:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "Images"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:113
msgid "Provide text descriptions in alt-text or captions for every non-text item such as diagrams, images, or icons."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:113
msgid "Avoid screenshots of text when possible."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:113
msgid "Make alt-text meaningful, not just descriptive. For action icons, for example, enter a description of the function rather than a description of its appearance."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:114
#, no-wrap
msgid "Links"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:118
msgid "Make links descriptive, so it is obvious where they will lead either from the text itself or from context. Avoid hyperlinks with names like “click here.”"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:118
msgid "Verify that all links work as described."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:124
msgid "Create tables with a logical order left to right, top to bottom."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:124
msgid "Avoid blank cells at the top or left of the table."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:124
msgid "Avoid merged cells that span multiple columns."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:125
#, no-wrap
msgid "Colors"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:130
msgid "Some elements in Markdown, such as admonitions, have an assigned color to assist with visual comprehension. In general they also have an assigned name; for example, the “danger” admonition displays a red box but also has the descriptor “danger” built into the description. But when creating a custom admonition, be aware that color cannot be the only means of communicating a command or level of warning."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:130
msgid "Any command that includes a sensory direction, such as *above* or *below*, *color*, *size*, *visual location* on the page, etc., should also include a direction that is communicable by only text description."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:130
msgid "When creating a graphical element, make sure that there is enough contrast between the foreground and background colors to be easy for a screen reader to interpret."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/contribute/style_guide.md:131
#, no-wrap
msgid "Headings"
